title: For Sale:  Stevens Vest Pocket Pistol .22 rimfire (Civil War Era derringer)
location: Wake Forest, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Stevens Vest Pocket Pistol .22 Cal. (short)  (Early model Approx 150 yrs old.) 
Heritage Firearm from my great grandfather. 
You wont see another one of these..!!!
Only 200 made in .22 caliber
Couldn't find any sold in auction or anywhere else in .22 Cal.
Truly a once in a lifetime find.

Still fully functional and fires!!!!

Single shot tip up model. Also called the "Fishtail"
First series of pistols made by Stevens arms who were taken over by Savage arms in 1920.

The frame and barrel are shiny with no traces of original blue on the sides of the barrel flats at the breech or even under the grips. (Not sure it was ever blued)

There is only a few pit marks and a few scratches in the metal on each side but very
minor.
The take down lock still engages solidly and hammer and spring engage fully.
The barrel looks to be smooth bore and has a few marks inside but no deep rust or pitting. It is stamped "Stevens & Co. Vest Pocket Pistol Chicopee Falls Mass."

The take-down, along with the grip screws are in beautiful shape and not knurled.
The serial number is 178 and matches on both frame (under grip) and on bottom of barrel that is covered by frame when closed.  So it was the 178th made out of 1000
units.

The cross hatching texture on top of hammer is still intact and can be felt with finger.

The grips are in great shape and not cracked and have slight handling marks as expected.


Gun Trader write up as follows:
This is a single shot pocket pistol chambered for the .22 and .30 rimfire Cartridges.
The .22 cal. version is rarely encountered and would be worth approximately 25% more than the values illustrated It has a 2.75" part octagonal barrel that pivots upward for loading. It has an external hammer and spur type trigger. The frame is nickel plated or blued, with a blued barrel. The odd shaped flared grips are made of rosewood. The first models were marked "Vest Pocket Pistol" only. Later models have the barrels marked "J. Stevens and Co. Chicopee Falls Mass."  There were approximately 1,000 made between  1864 and 1876

I put the condition between very good, to excellent, and from the pictures I have seen of the .30 cal ones sold this one is much cleaner.

Values:
Excellent                  V.G.                Good                 Fair               Poor
$4600                     3200               2100                 1200             950

Auction write-up:
Also called the "Kickup Model" pistol, manufactured between 1864 and 1876 with approximately 1,000 made. The pistol is marked "STEVENS & CO. VEST. POCKET. PISTOL/CHICOPEE FALLS MASS." on the top barrel flat, and features a German silver blade front sight, a notch in the hammer spur services as the rear sight, a tip up barrel and smooth odd shaped flared rosewood grips. The matching serial number is marked on frame under the grip and on the left side barrel flat, with the left grip panel hand numbered to gun.

I am posting this to serious collectors and buyers only..
I will not give this away period...!

I may send it to a Stevens expert and use his evaluation paper to get more out of it.

I figured a price of very good (3200) plus 25% (800) as it is a rare .22
which would be $4000

I even have a box of .22 shorts for it.. Although I would not fire it..!!!
My Dad let me shoot three rounds out of it when I was about 12 yrs old and I bugged the mess out of him to shoot it.. He said "this one time and don't ask again"
I have had it for years in my care and still haven't shot it since I was a kid.
But I know it will fire

If I send it off and have it appraised I will ask more for it.

Thanks for looking I have many more pictures at your request
I will also answer any questions I can about it.
Cash only... I can ship it without paperwork/permit due to age.

Beautiful piece of history family heirloom and I simply wont just give it away..!
nine one nine- 819- two nine two two.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Oehler Model 43 chronograph/ballistic laboratory
postcontent:
I bought this new and never used it, call Richard for more info. REDACTED
Incudes all parts and some extras. Was recently sent to Oehler to get it checked up and had a new battery installed. Comes with a $100 pelican style case.
 The Model 43 Personal Ballistics Laboratory is the ultimate instrument for the individual shooter. Used on your own shooting bench, it gives you more test power than is available at all but the most sophisticated industrial and government laboratories. As Rick Jamison says "You can learn more about real-world ballistics in a week with this unit than you could in years of studying books."

The only test data most of us see is muzzle velocity. Chamber pressure in the gun and downrange performance of the bullet is determined by a strange mix of folklore and computer programs. Unfortunately, most computer programs can only give old guesses displayed on the screen of a new computer. The Model 43 does much more; it actually measures pressure and measures downrange performance instead of guessing.

The Model 43 measures it all-

Muzzle Velocity · Proof Velocity · Peak Pressure · Pressure Rise Time · Pressure Curve · Area Under Curve · Time of Flight · Velocity at Target · Ballistic Coefficient · Group at Target Accurate Ballistics

PRESSURE READINGS

The Model 43 measures chamber pressure using a small strain gage glued over the chamber area of your gun. You need not drill any holes in the barrel, but bluing will likely be marred. Measuring the inside and outside diameters at the gage location provides a realistic pressure scale for the readings. You can reliably compare the pressure generated by your handloads with the pressures generated by factory ammunition fired in your gun. You can reliably compare the pressures from different handloads in the same gun. You can measure the pressures generated by wildcats where there are no standards or factory ammo available for comparison.

The Model 43 is not intended to measure SAAMI pressures. The Oehler Model 83 is made for SAAMI applications.

VELOCITY READINGS
The Model 43 measures several velocity readings on each shot. You can measure both muzzle and downrange velocities, and you have two PROOF CHANNELS to go along with the primary readings. You can even use the system to measure the muzzle velocities of machine guns. It can catch the muzzle velocity and rate of fire for each shot of a 30-round burst.

ACOUSTIC TARGET
If your bullets are supersonic at the target, you can use the optional acoustic target. Special microphones record the bullet's passage and the system displays the exact hit location, time-of-flight, ballistic coefficient, and the velocity at the target. The large window of the acoustic target makes it easy to measure actual ballistic coefficients over long ranges. 	
M43 Downrange Amplifier

M43 Microphone for Acoustic Target

 You can still get warranty service and parts.

REQUIRED COMPUTER FOR WINDOWS M-43 SOFTWARE
. The computer must have a 9-pin serial port. If you must use a “dongle” to convert from USB port to 9-pin port, we suggest the unit by IO Gear.

TEST RESULTS

The sample output page shows the complete test results and documentation provided by the Model 43. Complete test conditions are shown in the left column of the upper block. Complete gun information is shown in the center column. Complete load information is shown in the right column. All the individual results (velocities, time-of-flight to target, ballistic coefficient, pressure data and pressure curve) are shown for each shot. A summary block includes the statistical summary of each parameter for the whole group, and a target plot shows the actual group as recorded by the acoustic target.

The summary is followed by a condensed ballistic table computed with the measured muzzle velocity and the measured ballistic coefficient. What more could you ask?

title: For Sale/Trade:  Iver Johnson Safety Revolver .32 S&W
postcontent:
At one time I thought I might collect these little top-break revolvers, but I've changed my mind.

This is a little Iver Johnson revolver in .32 Smith and Wesson. It is in time and can be fired. The bore is somewhat worn but not corroded or pitted. The only problem is with the extractor, which needs to be jimmied a bit during reloading. That's not uncommon with these little old pistols.

The nickel finish is worn. The left grip has a chip out of the bottom, but is otherwise sound. 

Remember that this little revolver was designed to work with blackpowder cartridges. Modern loads should not be fired from it: it's strictly a handloader's affair (many use a cast round ball or pellet of 00 Buck over 1 gr. of Unique or Bullseye). In any even, you should have this piece checked by a competent gunsmith before firing.

I am not a dealer, but I do have a C&R license and will have to get your DL number for my bound book.

The revolver is already priced to sell. I'd rather keep it than to lower the price further. It's worth this much just for the parts!

title: For Sale:  NIB Smith & Wesson 329PD .44 Mag
postcontent:
Up for sale is my NIB Smith & Wesson model 329PD revolver in .44 Magnum caliber.  This is the lightweight Scandium framed revolver with Titanium cylinder, 4 inch barrel and red fiber optic front sight.  I purchased this gun new from Kames in Canton maybe a year ago, and it has been sitting in my safe unfired since then.  It was one of those "impulse buys" that I'm sure every gun owner is familiar with.  It's a beautiful looking revolver that stood out among a case full of stainless guns.  Unfortunately I have no real need for a lightweight .44 mag revolver and no time to enjoy it even if I did.  There is no point in leaving it sit in my safe untouched, so here is your chance to buy a new revolver at a discount.

As mentioned, the gun is brand new and has never been fired outside the factory.  That being said, there are some minor imperfections on the revolver from being handled in the store.  I'm pretty picky and the blemishes are minor, but I will describe them anyway for the sake of complete disclosure.  This gun was in the display case so it does have some light handling marks.  There is a visible turn line on the cylinder.  There is also a small scratch on the cylinder that I'm guessing was caused when the gun was being taken in and out of the display case.  There are also a few very light marks on the barrel of the revolver.  These are not deep scratches, just light marks.  There is also some powder residue left over from the test firing done at the factory.  Apparently S&W doesn't bother to clean the guns after testing.  Other than that, the revolver is perfect.  The wood grips are in perfect condition as well.  I bought the gun even with the blemishes because it was the only one they had left.  All minor imperfections are shown clearly in the pictures I have uploaded to Photobucket.  I have many high-res pics uploaded to Photobucket.  Just ask for the link and I will email it.

Everything that came with the gun when I purchased it is included in this sale.  That means the revolver itself, both the wood grips (installed) and rubber grips (never installed), blue plastic case, gun lock, keys, casing from the test round and all paperwork.

Must be over the age of 21 and legally able to purchase a firearm in the state of Ohio.  I will need to see a valid Ohio drivers license at time of sale.  CCW holders are preferred and will get first priority to buy, but a CCW is not a necessity.  Please email with any questions.  Asking price is $900 and this is a cash only sale.  I am not interested in any trades at this time.  I live in Canal Fulton, 44614.  Thanks for looking.

title: Want To Buy:  "No NY Sales"
postcontent:
To everyone saying "no NY sales" or "must be resident" on their ads... you are severely uninformed. It is NOT illegal for a non-resident (even New Yorkers) to purchase a firearm, parts or ammunition in Pennsylvania. To be specific, the NY UNSAFE Act does not apply to Pennsylvania, nor does it state anywhere in it's legislation that New Yorkers themselves cannot purchase firearms out of state, even via private sale.

If someone is willing to pay for your firearm and travels 45 minutes down Rt90 from NY to Erie PA, make the sale. Your fellow shooters in NY are hurting and desperate, do not make this worse for them than it already is with some asinine stipulation. If they have the cash and you have the product, make the sale, period.

Springfield’s popular polymer entry has become what every compact carrier has dreamed of — a duty-size pistol with a high-capacity option. With it’s newest package, the Springfield XD(M) 3.8 Compact –named for its 3.8-inch barrel, scaled own from the XD(M) 4.5–now comes with a Mag X-Tension, a high-cap magazine (we’re sure you got that from the name) that allows this one gun to go from a compact 9+1 to more of a 13+1 pseudo full-size option.

Thanks to the Mag X-Tension, you’ve got a short-barreled gun with a full-size grip. The interchangeable backstraps in three different sizes that are included with the XD(M) allow you to further personalize your grip length to match up with your capacity needs. It’s almost like you’re getting a two-for-one deal, and there’s nothing more American than that.

What could possibly be better? The other new wrinkle for the 3.8 compact is that it is now available in the caliber XD(M) fans have been clamoring for since the 3.8 was introduced: .45 ACP. This becomes the third offering in the compact line, joining 9mm and .40 S&W. We know, now you can die happy. When the original XD(M)s came to market  in .40 S&W it was just natural for expectations to grow that .45 would soon follow. Now, not only can you pick up the original XD(M) in .45, you can step out with its compact version in one of the personal defense world’s most popular calibers.

The 9+1 carry gun weighs in at just over 27 ounces with a height of 4.55 inches, and the Mag X-Tension adds just two ounces to the gun. With a fully ramped, Melonite-finished barrel and three-dot steel sights, the polymer frame gun is available with a forged steel black slide for $732. The stainless slide and black frame model is available for $797. It has a trigger pull between 5.5 and 7.7 lbs, features dovetail sights and comes with a carrying case, two stainless Megazines, mag loader, double mag pouch, three backstraps and three X-Tensions.

 There’s no doubt that fans of the XD(M) in .45 will find this compact model powerful and easy to conceal.
